Introduction to Git 

What is Git? 
Git is a distributed version control system (DVCS) used to track changes in files and coordinate work among multiple people. It helps developers manage code changes and collaborate efficiently. 
Key Concepts of Git 
1. Version Control: Tracks file changes over time. 
2. Distributed System: Each user has a full copy of the repository. 
3. Repository: A project folder with tracking data. 
4. Commit: A snapshot of changes. 
5. Branch: Separate line of development. 
6. Merge: Combines branches. 
7. Remote Repository: Online shared repo like GitHub. 

Common Git Commands 
git init - Create a repository 
git clone - Copy a repository 
git add - Stage changes 
git commit - Save changes 
git push - Upload changes 
git pull - Download updates 

Why Use Git? 
Git helps track changes, collaborate with teams, and manage different versions of files efficiently. 
